text=BOOK XXX. %0a%0aREMEDIES DERIVED FROM LIVING CREATURES. %0a%0aCHAP. 1. (1.)-THE ORIGIN OF THE MAGIC ART. %0a%0aIn former parts of this work, I have had occasion more than %0aonce, when the subject demanded it, to refute the impostures %0aof the magic art, and it is now my intention to continue still %0afurther my exposure thereof. Indeed, there are few subjects %0aon which more might be profitably said, were it only that, %0abeing, as it is, the most deceptive of all known arts, it has %0aexercised the greatest influence in every country and in nearly %0aevery age. And no one can be surprised at the extent of its %0ainfluence and authority, when he reflects that by its own ener¬ %0agies it has embraced, and thoroughly amalgamated with itself, %0athe three other sciences 1 which hold the greatest sway upon %0athe mind of man. %0a%0aThat it first originated in medicine, no one entertains a %0adoubt ; 2 or that, under the plausible guise of promoting health, %0ait insinuated itself among mankind, as a higher and more holy %0abrauch of the medical art. Then, in the next place, to pro¬ %0amises the most seductive and the most flattering, it has added %0aall the resources of religion, a subject upon which, at the pre¬ %0asent day, man is still entirely in the dark. Last of all, to %0acomplete its universal sway, it has incorporated with itself the %0aastrological art ; 3 there being no man who is not desirous to %0aknow his future destiny, or who is not ready to believe that %0athis knowledge may with the greatest certainty be obtained, %0aby observing the face of the heavens. The senses of men %0abeing thus enthralled by a three-fold bond, the art of magic %0ahas attained an influence so mighty, that at the present day %0aeven, it holds sway throughout a great part of the world, and %0arules the kings 4 of kings in the East. %0a%0a1 “ Artes.” Medicine, religion, and the art of divination. %0a%0a2 Ajasson remarks that, on the contrary, this is a subject of great doubt. %0a%0a1 “ Mathematicas artes.” %0a%0a4 The title of the ancient kings of Persia. %0a%0a%0apliny’s natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXX. %0a%0a%0a422 %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 2.-WHEN AND WHERE THE ART OF MAGIC ORIGINATED : %0a%0aBY WHAT PERSONS IT WAS FIRST PRACTISED. %0a%0aThere is no doubt that this art originated in Persia,® under %0aZoroaster, 6 this being a point upon which authors are generally %0aagreed; but whether there was only one Zoroaster, or whether %0ain later times there was a second person of that name, is a %0amatter which still remains undecided. Eudoxus, 7 who has %0aendeavoured to show that of all branches of philosophy the %0amagic art is the most illustrious and the most beneficial, in¬ %0aforms us that this Zoroaster existed six thousand years before %0athe death of Plato, an assertion in which he is supported by %0aAristotle. Hermippus,® again, an author who has written %0awith the greatest exactness on all particulars connected with %0athis art, and has commented upon the two millions 9 of verses %0aleft by Zoroaster, besides completing indexes to his several %0aworks, has left a statement, that Agonaces was the name of %0athe master from whom Zoroaster derived his doctrines, and %0athat he lived five thousand years before the time of the Trojan %0aWar. The first thing, however, that must strike us with Bur- %0aprise, is the fact that this art, and the traditions connected %0awith it, should have survived for so many ages, all written %0acommentaries thereon having perished in the meanwhile ; and %0athis, too, when there was no continuous succession of adepts, %0ano professors of note, to ensure their transmission. %0a%0aFor how few there are, in fact, who know anything, even %0aby hearsay, about the only professors of this art whose names %0ahave come down to us, Apusorus 10 and Zaratus of Media, %0aMarmarus and Arabantiphocus of Babylonia, and Tarmoendas %0aof Assyria, men who have left not the slightest memorials of %0atheir existence. But the most surprising thing of all is, that %0a%0a5 Or Bactriana, more properly. %0a%0aMagic, no doubt, has been the subject of belief from the earliest times, %0awhatever may have been the age of Zoroaster, the Zarathustra of theZend- %0aavesta, and the Zerdusht of the Persians. In the Zendavesta he is repre¬ %0asented as living in the reign of Gushtasp, generally identified with Darius %0aflystaspes. He probably lived at a period anterior to that of the Median %0aand Persian kings. Niebuhr regards him as a purely mythical personage %0a' See end of B. n. « See end of this Book. %0a%0a1 An exaggeration, of Oriental origin, most probably %0a16 These names have all, most probably, been transmitted to us in a cor¬ %0arupted form. Ajasson gives some suggestions as to their probable Eastern %0atomi and origin. %0a%0a%0aChnp. 2.] %0a%0a%0aWIIO FIRST PRACTISED MAGIC. %0a%0a%0a423 %0a%0a%0aHomer should he total]}’’ silent upon this art in his account 11 of %0athe Trojan War, while in his story of the wanderings of %0aUlysses, so much of the work should be taken up with it, that %0awe may justly conclude that the poem is based upon nothing %0aelse; if, indeed, we are willing to grant that his accounts of %0aProteus and of the songs of the Sirens are to be understood in %0athis sense, and that the stories of Circe and of the summoning %0aup of the shades below, 12 bear reference solely to the practices %0aof sorcerers. And then, too, to come to more recent times, no %0aone has told us how the art of sorcery reached Telmessus, 13 a %0acity devoted to all the services of religion, or at what period it %0acame over and reached the matrons of Thessaly; whose name 14 %0ahas long passed, in our part of the world, as the appellation of %0athose who practise an art, originally introduced among them¬ %0aselves even, from foreign lands. 15 For in the days of the Trojan %0aWar, Thessaly was still contented with such remedies 16 as she %0aowed to the skill of Chiron, and her only 17 lightnings were the %0alightnings hurled by Mars. 18 Indeed, for my own part, I am %0asurprised that the imputation of magical practices should have so %0astrongly attached to the people once under the sway of Achilles, %0athat Menander even, a man unrivalled for perception in lite¬ %0arary knowledge, has entitled one of his Comedies “The Thes¬ %0asalian Matron,” and has therein described the devices practised %0aby the females of that country in bringing down the moon %0afrom the heavens. 18 * I should have been inclined to think %0athat Orpheus had been the first to introduce into a country so %0anear his own, certain magical superstitions based upon the %0apractice of medicine, were it not the fact that Thrace, his %0anative land, was at that time totally a stranger to the magic %0aart. %0a%0a11 One among the many proofs, Ajasson says, that the Iliad and the %0aOdyssey belong to totally different periods. %0a%0a14 In reference to the Tenth Book of the Odyssey. %0a%0a13 See B. v. cc. 28, 29. Cicero mentions a college of Aruspices estab¬ %0alished at this city. %0a%0a14 The name “Thessala” was commonly used by the Romans to signify %0a%0aan enchantress, sorceress, or witch. See the story ot Apuleius, Books i. %0aand iii. 15 The countries of the East. %0a%0a16 Purely medicinal remedies. %0a%0a17 In contradistinction to lightnings elicited by the practice of Magic. %0a%0als A poetical figure, alluding to the “ thunderbolts of war,” as wielded %0aprobably by Achilles and other heroes of Thessaly. %0a%0alb * See B. ii. c. 9. %0a%0a%0a424 %0a%0a%0aplist’s natuhal histout. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXX. %0a%0a%0aThe first person, so far as I can ascertain, who wrote upon %0amagic, and whose works are still in existence, was Osthanes, 1 ’ %0awho accompanied Xerxes, the Persian king, in his expedition %0aagainst Greece. It was he who first 20 disseminated, as it were, %0athe germs of this monstrous art, and tainted therewith all parts %0aof the world through which the Persians passed. Authors %0a■who have made diligent enquiries into this subject, make men¬ %0ation of a second Zoroaster, a native of Proconnesus, as living a %0alittle before the time of Osthanes. That it was this samo %0aOsthanes, more particularly, that inspired the Greeks, not with %0aa fondness only, but a rage, for the art of magic, , is a fact be¬ %0ayond all doubt: though at the same time I would remark, %0athat in the most ancient times, and indeed almost invariably, %0ait w r as in this 21 branch of science, that was sought the highest %0apoint of celebrity and of literary renown. At all events, %0aPythagoras, we find, Empedocles, Democritus, and Plato, %0acrossed the seas, in order to attain a knowledge thereof, sub¬ %0amitting, to speak the truth, more to the evils of exile 22 than %0ato the mere inconveniences of travel. Returning home, it was %0aupon the praises of this art that they expatiated—it was this %0athat they held as one of their grandest mysteries. It was %0aDemocritus, too, who first drew attention to Apollobeches 23 of %0aCoptos, to Dardanus, 24 and to Phoenix : the works of Dardanus %0ahe sought in the tomb of that personage, and his own were %0acomposed in accordance with the doctrines there found. That %0athese doctrines should have been received by any portion of %0amankind, and transmitted to us by the aid of memory, is to %0ame surprising beyond anything I can conceive. 25 All the par¬ %0aticulars there found are so utterly incredible, so utterly re- %0a%0a19 Ajasson queries whether thisisapropername,or an epithet merely. %0a%0a20 Ajasson combats this assertion at considerable length, and with good %0areason. It is quite inadmissible. %0a%0a21 The mysteries of philosophy, as Ajasson remarks, were not necessarily %0aidentical with the magic art. %0a%0a22 In reality, Pythagoras was an exile from the tyranny of the ruler of %0aSamos, Plato from the court of Dionysius the Younger, and Democritus %0afrom the ignorance of his fellow-countrymen of Abdera. There is no %0adoubt that Pythagoras and Democritus made considerable researches into %0athe art of magic as practised in the East. %0a%0a23 Nothing is known of this writer. %0a%0a24 Dardanus, the ancestor of the Trojans, if he is the person here meant, %0ais said to have introduced the worship of the gods into Samothrace. %0a%0a25 The works of Homer were transmitted in a similar manner. %0a%0a%0aChap. 3.] WHETHER MAGIC WAS EVER PRACTISED IK ITALY. 425 %0a%0avolting, that those even who admire Democritus in other %0arespects, are strong in their denial that these works were really %0awritten by him. Their denial, however, is in vain; for it %0awas he, beyond all doubt, who had the greatest share in fas¬ %0acinating men’s minds with these attractive chimseras. %0a%0aThere is also a marvellous coincidence, in the fact that the %0atwo arts — medicine, I mean, and magic — were developed %0asimultaneously : medicine by the writings of Hippocrates, and %0amagic by the works of Democritus, about the period of the %0aPeloponnesian War, which was waged in Greece in the year %0aof the City of Rome 300. %0a%0aThere is another sect, also, of adepts in the magic art, who %0aderive their origin from Moses, 26 Jaimes, 27 and Lotapea, 28 Jews %0aby birth, 29 but many thousand years posterior to Zoroaster : and %0aas much more recent, again, is the branch of magic culti¬ %0avated in Cyprus. 60 In the time, too, of Alexander the Great, %0athis profession received no small accession to its credit from %0athe influence of a second Osthanes, who had the honour of %0aaccompanying that prince in his expeditions, and who, evi¬ %0adently, beyond all doubt, travelled S1 over every part of the %0aworld. %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 3.-WHETHER MAGIC WAS EVER PRACTISED IK ITALY. AT %0a%0aWHAT PERIOD THE SENATE FIRST FORBADE HUMAN SACRIFICES. %0a%0aIt is clear that there are early traces still existing of the %0a%0a26 Moses, no doubt, was represented by the Egyptian priesthood as a %0amagician, in reference more particularly to the miracles wrought by him %0abefore Pharaoh. From them the Greeks would receive the notion. %0a%0a27 In 2 Tim. iii. 8, we find the words, “Now as Jannes and Jambres %0a■withstood Moses, so do these also resist the truth.’’ Eusebius, in his Prcc- %0aparatio Evangelica, B. ix., states that Jannes and Jambres, or Mambres, %0awere the names of Egyptian writers, who practised Magic, and opposed %0aMoses before Pharaoh. This contest was probably represented by the %0aEgyptian priesthood as merely a dispute between two antagonistic schools %0aof Idagic. %0a%0a28 Of this person nothing is known. The former editions mostly have %0a“ Jotapea.’’ “ Jotapata” was the name of a town in Syria, the birthplace %0aof Josephus. %0a%0a29 lie is mistaken here as to the nation to which Jannes belonged. %0a%0aso By some it has been supposed that this bears reference to Christianity, %0aas introduced into Cyprus by the Apostle Barnabas Owing to the miracles %0awrought in the infancy of the Church, the religion of the Christians was %0avery generally looked upon as a sort of Magic. The point is very doubtful. %0a%0a31 ilis itinerary, Ajassou remarks, would have been a great curiosity. %0a%0a%0a426 %0a%0a%0aflint's natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Hook XXX. %0a%0a%0aintroduction of magic into Italy; in our laws of the Twelve %0aTables for instance; besides other convincing proofs, which I %0ahave already noticed in a preceding Book. 33 At last, in the %0ayear of the City 657, Cneius Cornelius Lentulus and P. Lici- %0anius Crassus being consuls, a decree forbidding human sacri¬ %0afices 33 was passed by the senate ; from which period the cele¬ %0abration of these horrid rites ceased in public, and, for some ‘ %0atime, altogether. %0a%0aCHAP. 4.-THE DRUIDS OF THE GALLIC PROVINCES. %0a%0aThe Gallic provinces, too, were pervaded by the magic art,' 5 %0aand that even down to a period within memory ; for it was %0athe Emperor Tiberius that put down their Druids, 36 and all that %0atribe of wizards and physicians. But why make further men¬ %0ation of these prohibitions, with reference to an art which has %0anow crossed the very Ocean even, and has penetrated to the %0avoid 37 recesses of Nature? At the present day, struck with %0afascination, Britannia still cultivates this art, and that, with %0aceremonials so august, that she might almost seem 38 to have %0abeen the first to communicate them to the people of Persia. 39 %0aTo such a degree are nations throughout the whole world, %0atotally different as they are and quite unknown to one another, %0ain accord upon this one point! %0a%0a32 B. xxviii. c. 4. %0a%0a33 These sacrifices forming the most august rite of the Magic art, as %0apractised in Italy. %0a%0a34 That this art was still practised in secret in the days of Pliny himself, %0awe learn from the testimony of Tacitus (Annals, II. 69), in his account of %0athe enquiries instituted on the death of Germanicus. %0a%0a35 More particularly in the worship of their divinity lieu or Hesus, the %0agod of war. %0a%0a36 This he did officially, but not effectually, and the Druids survived as %0aa class for many centuries both in Gaul and Britain. %0a%0a37 He alludes to the British shores bordering on the Atlantic. See B. %0axix. c. 2. %0a%0a33 It is a curious fact that the round towers of Ireland bear a strong re¬ %0asemblance to those, the ruins of which are still to be seen on the plains of %0aancient Persia. %0a%0a39 “ Ut dedisse Persis videri possit.” This might possibly mean, “That %0aPersia might almost seem to have communicated it direct to Britain.” Ajas- %0ason enumerates the following superstitions of ancient Britain, as bearing %0aprobable marks of an Oriental origin: the worship of the stars, lakes, %0aforests, and rivers; the ceremonials used in cutting the plants samiolus, %0aselago, and mistletoe, and the virtues attributed to the adder’s egg. %0a%0a%0aChap. 5.] THE VARIOUS BRANCHES OF MAGIC. 427 %0a%0aSuch being the fact, then, we cannot too highly appreciate %0athe obligation that is due to the Roman people, for having put %0aan end to those monstrous rites, in accordance with which, to %0amurder a man was to do an act of the greatest devoutness, and %0ato eat 40 his flesh was to secure the highest blessings of health. %0a%0aCHAP. 5. (2.)—THE VARIOUS BRANCHES OF MAGIC. %0a%0aAccording to what Osthanes tells us, there are numerous %0asorts of magic. It is practised 41 with water, for instance, with %0aballs, by the aid of the air, of the stars, of lamps, basins, hatchets, %0aand numerous other appliances; means by which it engages %0ato grant a foreknowledge of things to come, as well as converse %0awith ghosts and spirits of the dead. All these practices, how¬ %0aever, have been proved by the Emperor Hero, in our own day, %0ato be so many false and chimaerical illusions; entertaining as %0ahe did a passion for the magic art, unsurpassed even by his %0aenthusiastic love for the music of the lyre, and for the songs of %0atragedy; so strangely did his elevation to the highest point %0aof human fortune act upon the deep-seated vices of his mind ! %0aIt was his leading desire to command the gods of heaven, and %0ano aspiration could he conceive more noble than this. Never %0adid person lavish more favours upon any one of the arts ; and %0afor the attainment of this, his favourite object, nothing was %0awanting to him, neither riches, nor power, nor aptitude at %0alearning, and what not besides, at the expense of a suffering %0aworld. %0a%0aIt is a boundless, an indubitable proof, I say, of the utter %0afalsity of this art, that such a man as Nero abandoned it; and %0awould to heaven that he had consulted the shades below, and %0aany other spirits as well, in order to be certified in his sus¬ %0apicions, rather than commissioned the denizens of stews and %0abrothels to make those inquisitions of his [with reference to %0athe objects of his jealousy]. For assuredly there can be no %0a%0a40 Ajasson seems inclined to suggest that this may possibly bear reference %0ato the Christian doctrines of redemption and the Sacrament of the Lord's %0aSupper. %0a%0a41 These kinds of divination, rather than magic, were called hydromancy, %0asphaeromancy, aeromancy, astromancy, lychnomancy, lecanomancy, and %0aaxinomancy. See Rabelais, B. iii. c. 25, where a very full account is given %0aof the Magic Art, as practised by the ancients. Coffee-grounds, glair of %0aeggs, and rose-leaves, are still used in France for purposes ot divination %0aby the superstitious. %0a%0a%0a428 %0a%0a%0apliny’s natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXX. %0a%0a%0asuperstition, however barbarous and ferocious the rites which %0ait sanctions, that is not more tolerant than the imaginations %0awhich he conceived, and owing to which, by a series of blood¬ %0astained crimes, our abodes were peopled with ghosts. %0a%0aCHAP. 6.—THE SUBTERFUGES PRACTISED BY THE MAGICIANS. %0a%0aThe magicians, too, have certain modes of evasion, as, for %0ainstance, that the gods will not obey, or even appear to, persons %0awho have freckles upon the skin. Was this perchance the %0aobstacle 42 in Nero’s way ? As for his limbs, there was 43 nothing %0adeficient in them. And then, besides, he was at liberty to %0amake choice of the days prescribed by the magic ritual: it %0awas an easy thing for him to make choice of sheep whose %0acolour was no other than perfectly black: and as to sacrificing %0ahuman beings, there was nothing in the world that gave him %0agreater pleasure. The Magian Tiridates 44 was at his court, %0ahaving repaired thither, in token of our triumph over Armenia, %0aaccompanied by a train which cost dear to the provinces through %0awhich it passed. For the fact was, that he was unwilling to %0atravel by water, it being a maxim with the adepts in this art %0athat it is improper to spit into the sea or to profane that element %0aby any other of the evacuations that are inseparable from the %0ainfirmities of human nature. He brought with him, too, %0aseveral other Magi, and went so far as to initiate the emperor %0ain the repasts 45 of the craft; and yet the prince, for all he had %0abestowed a kingdom upon the stranger, found himself unable %0ato receive at his hands, in return, this art. %0a%0aWe may rest fully persuaded then, that magic is a thing %0adetestable in itself. Frivolous and lying as it is, it still bears, %0ahowever, some shadow of truth upon it; though reflected, in %0areality, by the practices of those who study the arts of secret %0apoisoning, and not the pursuits of magic. Let any one picture %0ato himself the lies of the magicians of former days, when he %0alearns what has been stated by the grammarian Apion, 46 a %0a%0a42 Suetonius says that his body was full of foul spots. %0a%0a43 It was probably a doctrine of Magic, that an adept must not be de¬ %0aficient in any of his limbs. %0a%0a44 After being conquered by the Roman general, Corbulo, he received %0athe crown of Armenia from Nero, a.d. 63. %0a%0a45 All vegetable substances were divided, according to their doctrine, into %0athe pure and the impure, the rule being strictly observed at their repasts. %0a%0a46 See end of this Rook. %0a%0a%0ad,ap. 7.] REMEDIES DERITED FROM THE MOI.F,. 429 %0a%0aperson whom I remember seeing myself when young. He %0atells us that the plant cynocephalia, 47 known in Egypt as %0a“osiritis,” is useful for divination, and is a preservative against %0aall the malpractices of magic, but that if a person takes it out %0aof the ground entire, he will die upon the spot. He asserts, %0aalso, that he himself had raised the spirits 48 of the dead, in %0aorder to make enquiry of Homer in reference to his native %0acountry and his parents; but he does not dare, he tells us, %0adisclose the answer he received. %0a%0aCHAP. 7. (3.)—OPINIONS OF THE MAGICIANS RELATIVE TO THE %0aMOLE. FIVE REMEDIES DERIVED FROM IT. %0a%0aLet the following stand as a remarkable proof of the frivo¬ %0alous nature of the magic art. Of all animals it is the mole %0athat the magicians admire most ! a creature that has been %0astamped with condemnation by Nature in so many waj r s; %0adoomed as it is to perpetual blindness, 49 and adding to this %0adarkness a life of gloom in the depths of the earth, and a state %0amore nearly resembling that of the dead and buried. There %0ais no animal in the entrails of which they put such implicit %0afaith, no animal, they think, better suited for the rites of reli¬ %0agion ; so much so, indeed, that if a person swallows the heart of %0aa mole, fresh from the body and still palpitating, he will receive %0athe gift of divination, they assure us, and a foreknowledge of %0afuture events. Tooth-ache, they assert, may be cured by %0ataking the tooth of a live mole, and attaching it to the body. %0aAs to other statements of theirs relative to this animal, we %0ashall draw attention to them on the fitting occasions, and shall %0aonly add here that one of the most probable ot all their asser¬ %0ations is, that the mole neutralizes the bite of the shrew-mouse; %0aseeing that, as already 60 stated, the very earth even that is %0afound in the rut of a cart-wheel, acts as a remedy in such a %0acase. %0a%0a47 See B. xxv. c. 80. %0a%0a48 Like the assertions of the famous impostor of the close of the last %0acentury, Count Cagliostro. %0a%0a49 A mistake, of course; and one for which there is little excuse, as its %0a%0aeyes are easily perceptible. It is not improbable, however, that it was an %0aimpression with the ancients that its sight, is impeded by the horny covering %0aof its eyes. 5t > In B. xxix. c. 27. %0a%0a%0a430 %0a%0a%0apmst’s natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXX. %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 8.-THE OTHER REMEDIES DERIVED FROM LIVING CUEATlKKs, %0a%0aCLASSIFIED ACCORDING TO THE RESPECTIVE DISEASES. REMEDIES %0a%0aFOR TOOTH-ACHE. %0a%0aBut to proceed with the remedies for tooth-ache—the magi- %0acians tell us, that it may be cured by using the ashes of the %0ahead of a dog that has died in a state of madness. The head, %0ahowever, must he burnt without the flesh, and the ashes %0ainjected with oil of Cyprus 51 into the ear on the side affected. %0aFor the same purpose also, the left eye-tooth of a dog is used, %0athe gum of the affected tooth being lanced with it; one of the %0avertebrae also of a dragon or of an enhydris, which is a male %0awhite serpent. 52 The eye-tooth, too, of this last, is used for %0ascarifying the gums; and when the pain affects the teeth of the %0aupper jaw, they attach to the patient two of the upper teeth of %0athe serpent, and, similarly, two of the lower ones for tooth-ache %0ain the lower jaw. Persons who go in pursuit of the crocodile, %0aanoint themselves with the fat of this animal. The gums are %0aalso scarified with the frontal bones of a lizard, taken from %0ait at full moon, and not allowed to touch the ground: or else %0athe mouth is rinsed with a decoction of dogs’ teeth in wiue, %0aboiled down to one half. %0a%0aAshes of dogs’ teeth, mixed with honey, are useful for %0adifficult dentition in children, and a dentifrice is similarly %0aprepared from them. Hollow teeth are plugged with ashes of %0aburnt mouse-dung, or with a lizard’s liver, dried. To eat a %0asnake’s heart, or to wear it, attached to the body, is considered %0ahighly efficacious. There are some among the magicians, who %0arecommend a mouse to be eaten twice a month, as a preventive %0aof tooth-ache. Earth-worms, boiled in oil and injected into %0athe ear on the side affected, afford considerable relief: ashes, %0atoo, of burnt earth-worms, introduced into carious teeth, make %0athem come out easily; and, used as a friction, they allay pains %0ain such of the teeth as are sound: the proper way of burning %0athem is in an earthen potsherd. They are useful, too, boiled %0awith root of the mulberry-tree in squill vinegar, and employed %0aas a collutory for the teeth. The small worm that is found %0ain the plant known as Venus’ 5