ber of them. Snails, however, have a juice, it should %0ahe remembered, which imparts to the breath an offensive smell. %0a%0a77 See Horace, Epode xii. 1. 5. %0a%0a78 Hence, perhaps, the practice of nursing lap-dogs. %0a%0a70 See B. iii. c. 30, and Note 2, p. 267. %0a%0aso J n France and Italy, snails are considered a delicacy by some. Snail %0amilk is sometimes used medicinally in England for consumptive patients: %0ait is doubtful with what effect. %0a%0a81 Or fish-sauce. See B. xxxi. c. 43. %0a%0a%0a438 %0a%0a%0apliny’s natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Hook XXX. %0a%0a%0aFor patients troubled with spitting of blood,- they are remark¬ %0aably good, the shell being first removed, and the contents %0abraised and administered in water. The most esteemed kinds %0aof all are those of Africa—those which come from Iol, 82 in %0aparticular—of Astypalaea, and, after them, those of JEtna, in %0aSicily, those I mean of moderate size, for the large ones are %0ahard, and destitute of juice. The Balearic snails, called “ca- %0avaticae,” from being found in caverns, are much esteemed; and %0aso, too, are those from the islands of Capreae. 83 Those of Greece, %0aon the other hand, are never used for food, either old or %0afresh. %0a%0aIliver snails, and those with a white shell, have a strong, %0arank, juice, and forest snails are by no means good for the %0astomach, having a laxative effect upon the bowels; the same, %0atoo, with all kinds of small snails. Sea-snails, 84 on the other %0ahand, are more beneficial to the stomach; but it is for pains %0ain that region that the) 1, are found the most efficacious: the %0abest plan, it is said, is to eat them alive, of whatever kind %0athey may happen to be, with vinegar. In addition to these, %0athere are the snails called “ aceratoe,” 85 with a bi’oad shell, and %0afound in numerous localities: of the uses to which they arc %0aput we shall 86 speak further on the appropriate occasions. The %0acraw of poultry, dried and sprinkled in the drink, or else used %0afresh and grilled, has a soothing effect upon pectoral catarrhs %0aand coughs attended with phlegm. 87 Snails, beaten up raw %0aand taken in three cyathi of warm water, allay cough. A %0apiece of dog’s skin, wrapped round any one of the fingers, af¬ %0afords relief to patients suffering from catarrh. A broth made %0aof boiled partridges is strengthening for the stomach. %0a%0aCHAP. 16.-REMEDIES FOR PAINS IN THE LIVER, AND FOR 8PITTIN0 %0a%0aOF BLOOD. %0a%0aFor tbe cure of pains in the liver, a wild weasel is taken %0awith the food, or the liver only of that animal; a ferret also, %0aroasted like a sucking-pig. In cases of asthma, millepedes %0aare used, thrice seven of them being soaked in Attic honey, %0a%0a82 See B. v. c. 20. 83 See B. iii. c. 12. 34 Our periwinkles. %0a%0a85 Daleckamps takes this to mean “without horns and Hardouin is %0aof opinion that it means “ genuine ” or “ unmixed.” In either sense, %0athe word is derived from the Greek. %0a%0a86 He has omitted to do so. %0a%0a%0a81 “ Humida tussis.’ %0a%0a%0aChap. 17.] REMEDIES EOR AFFECTIONS OF THE SPLEEN. 43.9 %0a%0aand taken internally by the aid of a reed i 88 for all vessels, it %0ashould be remembered, turn black on coming in contact with %0athem. Some persons grill one sextarius of these insects on a %0aflat pan, till they become white, and then mix them with %0ahoney. There are some authorities who call this insect a %0a“centipede,” and recommend it to be given in warm water. %0aSnails are administered to persons subject to fainting fits, %0aalienation of the senses, and vertigo : for which purposes, a %0asnail is beaten up, shell and all, with three cyathi of raisin %0awine, and the mixture is administered warm with the drink, %0afor nine days at most. Others, again, give-one snail the first %0aday, two the second, three the third, two the fourth, and one %0athe fifth; a mode of treatment also adopted for the cure of %0aasthma and of abscesses. %0a%0aThere is, according to some authorities, an insect resem¬ %0abling the locust in appearance, destitute of wings, and known %0aby the Greek name of “ troxallis,” it being without a name in %0aLatin: a considerable number of writers, however, consider %0ait as identical with the insect known to us as “ gryllus.” 89 %0aTwenty of these insects, they say, should be grilled, and taken %0ain honied wine, by patients troubled with hardness of breath¬ %0aing or spitting of blood. Some persons pour pure grape-juice, 90 %0aor sea-water, upon unwashed snails, and then boil and eat %0athem for food; or else they bruise tbe snails, shells and all, %0aand take them with this grape-juice. A similar method is %0aalso adopted for the cure of cough. Honey in which the bees %0ahave died, is particularly good for the cure of abscesses. For %0aspitting of blood a vulture’s lungs are used, burnt upon vine %0alogs, and mixed with half the quantity of pomegranate blos¬ %0asoms, or with the same proportion of quince and lily blossom : %0athe whole being taken morning and evening, in wine, if there %0ais no fever ; but where there are symptoms of lever, instead of %0awine, water is used in which quinces have been boiled. %0a%0aCHAP. 17.-REMEDIES FOR AFFECTIONS OF THE SPLEEN. %0a%0aAccording to the prescriptions given by the magicians, a %0afresh sheep’s milt is the best application for pains in the spleen, %0aihe person who applies it uttering these words: “ I his I do %0a%0a88 See c. 12 of this Book. . %0a%0a89 Our “ cricket.” The troxallis was probably a kind of locust, still %0aknown to naturalists by that name. %0a%0aso o Protropum.” "Wine of the first running. %0a%0a%0a440 %0a%0a%0aPLINY’S NATURAL niSTORT. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXX. %0a%0a%0afor the cure of the spleen.” This done, it is enjoined that the %0amilt should be covered up with mortar in the wall of the %0apatient’s sleeping-room, and sealed with a ring, a charm 91 being %0arepeated thrice nine times. A dog’s milt, removed from the %0aanimal while still alive, taken with the food, is a cure for dis¬ %0aeases of the spleen : some, again, attach it fresh to that part %0aof the patient’s body. Others give the patient—without his %0aknowing it—the milt of a puppy two days old, to eat, in %0asquill vinegar ; the milt, too, of a hedge-hog is similarly %0aused. Ashes of burnt snails are employed, in combination %0awith linseed, nettle-seed, and honey, the treatment being per¬ %0asisted in till the patient is thoroughly cured. %0a%0aA green lizard has a remedial effect, suspended alive in an %0aearthen vessel, at the entrance of the sleeping-room of the %0apatient, who, every time he enters or leaves it, must take care %0ato touch it with his hand : the head, too, of a horned owl, re¬ %0aduced to ashes and incorporated with an unguent; honey, also, %0ain which the bees have died ; and spiders, the one known as %0athe “ lycos” 92 in particular 1 . %0a%0aCHAP. 18 . —REMEDIES FOR PAINS IN THE SIDE AND IN THE LOINS. %0a%0aFor pains in the side, the heart of a hoopoe is highly es¬ %0ateemed ; ashes, too, of burnt snails, that have been boiled in %0aa ptisan, snails being sometimes applied in the form of a lini¬ %0ament, alone. Potions employed for this purpose have a sprink¬ %0aling in them of the ashes of a mad dog’s skull. For the cure %0aof lumbago, the spotted lizard 93 from beyond seas is used: %0athe head and intestines being first removed, the body is boiled %0ain wine, with half a denarius of black poppy, and the decoc¬ %0ation is taken in drink. Green lizards, also, are taken with %0athe food, the feet and head being first removed ; or else three %0asnails are crushed, shells and all, and boiled with fifteen pepper¬ %0acorns in wine. The feet of an eagle are wrenched off in a %0acontrary direction to the joint, and the right foot is attached %0ato the right side, the left foot to the left, according as the %0apains are situate. The millepede, 91 which we have spoken of %0a%0a91 “Carmen.” Holland says “the aforesaid charm:” but this does %0anot appear from the context. From the account, however, given by Marcus %0aEmpiricus, we learn that the charm, thus repeated twenty-seven times, is %0athe same as that already given. %0a%0a9i Or “ wolf.” See B. xi. c. 28. 93 See B. xxix. c. 28. %0a%0a91 Or woodlouse. See B. xxix. c. 39. %0a%0a%0aChap. 19.] %0a%0a%0aREMEDIES FOR DYSENTERY. %0a%0a%0a441 %0a%0a%0aas being called tbe “ oniscos,” is a cure for these pains, %0ataken, in doses of one denarius, in two cyathi of wine. %0aThe magicians recommend an earth-worm to be put in a %0awooden dish, which has been split and mended with iron %0awire; which done, some water must be taken up with the dish, %0athe worm drenched with it and buried in the spot from %0awhich it was taken, and the water drunk from the dish. %0aThey assert, also, that this is a marvellously excellent cure for %0asciatica. %0a%0aCITAP. 19. (7.)—REMEDIES FOR DYSENTERY. %0a%0aDysentery is cured by taking the broth of a leg of mutton, %0aboiled with linseed in water ; by eating old ewe-milk cheese; %0aor by taking mutton suet boiled in astringent wine. This %0alast is good, too, for the iliac passion, and for inveterate coughs. %0aDysentery is removed also, by taking a spotted lizard from %0abeyond seas, boiled down till the skin only is left, the head, %0afeet, and intestines, being first removed. A couple of snails %0aalso, and an egg, are beaten up, shells and all, in both cases, %0aand made lukewarm in a new vessel, with some salt, three %0acyathi of water, and two cyathi of raisin-wine or date-juice, %0athe decoction being taken in drink. Ashes, too, of burnt snails, %0aare very serviceable, taken in wine with a modicum of resin. %0a%0aThe snails without shells, which we have 95 mentioned as %0abeing mostly found in Africa, are remarkably useful for dy¬ %0asentery, five of them being burnt with half a denarius of gum %0aacacia, and taken, in doses of two spoonfuls, in myrtle wine or %0aany other kind of astringent wine, with an equal quantity of %0awarm water. Some persons employ all kinds of African snails %0aindiscriminately in this manner ; while others, again, make use %0aof a similar number of African snails or broad-shelled snails, %0aas an injection, in preference : in cases, too, where the flux is %0aconsiderable, they add a piece of gum acacia, about the size of %0aa bean. For dysentery and tenesmus, the cast-off slough of a %0asnake is boiled in a pewter vessel with oil of roses: if pre¬ %0apared in any other kind of vessel, it is applied with an instru¬ %0ament made of pewter. Chicken-broth is also used as a remedy %0afor these affections; but the broth of an old cock, strongly %0asalted, acts more powerfully as a purgative upon the bowels. %0aA pullet’s craw, grilled and administered with salt and oil, has %0a%0a95 In B. xxix. c. 36. %0a%0a%0a4-12 %0a%0a%0aplisy’s natural bistort. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXX. %0a%0a%0aa soothing effect upon coeliac affections; but it is absolutely %0anecessary that neither fowl nor patient should have eaten %0acorn 96 for some time before. Pigeons’ dung, also, is grilled and %0ataken in drink. The flesh of a ring-dove, boiled in vinegar, %0ais curative of dysentery and cocliac affections: and for the cure %0aof the former, a thrush is recommended, roasted with myrtle- %0aberries ; a blackbird, also; or honey, boiled, in which the bees %0ahave died. %0a%0aCHAP. 20 .- REMEDIES FOR THE ILIAC PASSION, AND FOR OTHF.K %0a%0aMALADIES OF THE DOWELS. %0a%0aOne of the most dangerous of maladies is that known by the %0aname of “ ileos:” 97 it may be combatted, they say, by tearing %0aa bat asunder, and taking the blood, or by rubbing the abdo¬ %0amen with it. Diarrhoea is arrested more particularly by taking %0asnails, prepared in manner already 98 mentioned for cases of %0aasthma; the ashes, also, of snails burnt alive, administered in %0aastringent wine; the liver of poultry grilled; the dried craw %0aof poultry, a part that is usually thrown away, mixed with %0apoppy-juice—in some cases it is used fresh, grilled, and taken %0ain wine—partridge broth ; the craw of partridges beaten up by %0aitself in red wine ; a wild ringdove boiled in oxycrate ; a sheep’s %0amilt, grilled and beaten up in wine; or else pigeons’ dung, %0aapplied with honey. The crop of an ossifrage, dried and taken %0ain drink, is remarkably useful for patients whose digestion is %0aimpaired—indeed, its good effects may be felt if they only hold %0ait in the hand while eating. Hence it is that some persons %0awear it attached to the body as an amulet; a practice which %0amust not be too long continued, it being apt to cause a wasting %0aof the flesh. The blood, too, of a drake has an astringent %0aeffect. %0a%0aFlatulency is dispelled by eating snails; and griping pains %0ain the bowels, by taking a sheep’s milt grilled, with wine; a %0awild ringdove boiled in oxycrate; the fat of an otis" in wine; or %0athe ashes of an ibis, burnt without the feathers, administered in %0adrink. Another prescription mentioned for griping pains in %0athe bowels is of a very marvellous nature : if a duck, they say, %0ais applied to the abdomen, the malady will pass into the bird, %0a%0a96 See B. xxix. c. 36. 97 The iliac passion, or ileus volvulus. %0a%0a9S In c. 16 of this Book. %0a%0a99 A kind of bustard. See B. x. cc. 29, 50, and c. 45 of this Book. %0a%0a%0aChap. 21.] REMEDIES TOR URINARY CALCULI. 443 %0a%0aand it will die. 1 Gripings of the bowels are treated also with %0aboiled honey in which the bees have died. %0a%0aColic is most effectually cured by taking a roasted lark with %0athe food. Some recommend, however, that it should be burnt %0ato ashes in a new vessel, feathers and all, and then pounded %0aand taken for four consecutive days, in doses of three spoonfuls, %0ain water. Some say that the heart of this bird should be %0aattached to the thigh, and, according to others, the heart should %0abe swallowed fresh, quite warm, in fact. There is a family %0aof consular dignity, known as the Asprenates, 2 two brothers, %0amembers of which, were cured of colic; the one by eating a %0alark and wearing its heart in a golden bracelet; the other, by %0aperforming a certain sacrifice in a chapel built of raw bricks, %0ain form of a furnace, and then blocking up the edifice the mo¬ %0ament the sacrifice was concluded. The ossifrage has a single %0aintestine only, which has the marvellous property of digesting %0aall that the bird has swallowed: the extremity of this intes¬ %0atine, it is well known, worn as an amulet, is an excellent %0aremedy for colic. %0a%0aThere are certain concealed maladies incident to the intes¬ %0atines, in relation to which there are some marvellous statements %0amade. If to the stomach and chest, more particularly, blind %0apuppies are applied, and suckled with milk from the patient’s %0amouth, 3 the virulence of the malady, it is said, will be trans¬ %0aferred to them, and in the end they will die : on opening %0athem, too, the causes of the malady will be sure to be dis¬ %0acovered. In all such cases, however, the puppies must be %0aallowed to die, and must be buried in the earth. According %0ato what the magicians say, if the abdomen is touched with a %0ahat’s blood, the person will be proof against colic for a whole %0ayear: when a patient, too, is attacked with the pains of colic, %0aif he can bring himself to drink the water in which he has %0awashed his feet, he will experience a cure. %0a%0aCHAP. 21. (8.)-REMEDIES FOR URINARY CALCULI AND %0a%0aAFFECTIONS OF THE BLADDER. %0a%0aFor the cure of urinary calculi, it is a good plan to rub %0a%0a1 See c. 14 of this Book, where a similar notion is mentioned. %0a%0a1 There were three consuls of this name, L. Nonius Asprenas, a.d. 7; %0aL. Nonius Asprenas, a.d. 29; and P. Nonius Asprenas, a.d. 38. They %0aare mentioned also by Suetonius, Tacitus, Dion Cassius, Frontinus, and %0aSeneca. ’ 3 See c. 14 of this Book. %0a%0a%0a444 %0a%0a%0apltny’s natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXX. %0a%0a%0athe abdomen with mouse-dung. The flesh of a hedge-hog is %0aagreeable eating, they sa)', if killed with a single blow upon %0athe head, before it has had time to discharge its urine 3 * upon %0aits body: [persons 4 who eat this flesh, it is said, will never by %0aany possibility suffer from strangury.] The flesh of a hedge¬ %0ahog thus killed, is a cure for urinary obstructions of the blad¬ %0ader; and the same, too, with fumigations made therewith. If, %0aon the other hand, the animal has discharged its urine upon its %0abody, those who eat the flesh will be sure to be attacked by %0astrangury, it is said. As a lithontriptic, 5 earth-worms are %0arecommended, taken in ordinary wine or raisin wine; or else %0aboiled snails, prepared the same way 6 as for the cure of asthma. %0aFor the cure of urinary obstructions, snails are taken from the %0ashells, pounded, and administered in one cyathus of wine, three %0athe first day, two the second, and one the third. For the ex¬ %0apulsion of calculi, the empty shells are reduced to ashes and %0ataken in drink: the liver also of a water-snake, and the ashes %0aof burnt scorpions are similarly employed, or are taken with %0abread or eaten with a locust. For the same purpose, the %0asmall grits that are found in the gizzard of poultry or in the %0acraw of the ringdove, are beaten up and sprinkled in the %0apatient’s drink; the craw, too, of poultry is taken, dried, or if %0afresh, grilled. %0a%0aFor urinary calculi and other obstructions of the bladder, %0adung of ring-doves is taken, with beans; ashes also of wild %0aring-doves’ feathers, mixed with vinegar and honey; the in¬ %0atestines of those birds, reduced to ashes, and administered in %0adoses of three spoonfuls; a small clod from a swallow’s nest, %0adissolved in warm water; the dried crop of an ossifrage; the %0adung of a turtle-dove, boiled in honied wine; or the broth of %0aa boiled turtle-dove. %0a%0aIt is very beneficial also for urinary affections to eat thrushes %0awith myrtle-berries, or grasshoppers grilled on a shallow-pan; %0aor else to take the millepedes, known as “ ouisei,” 7 in drink. %0aFor pains in the bladder, a decoction of lambs’ feet is used. %0a%0a3 * See B. viii. c. 56. %0a%0a4 This passage is omitted by Sillig as an evident interpolation from the %0acontext a couple of lines below. %0a%0a5 The belief in lithontriptics can hardly be said to exist at the present %0aday. Ajasson refers to the grant made by the British Parliament of £5000 %0ato Mrs. Stephens for her lithontriptic! ! %0a%0a6 In c. 16 of this Book. 7 See B. xxix. c. 39. %0a%0a%0aChap. 22.] REMEDIES FOR THE GENERATIVE ORGANS. 445 %0a%0aChicken-broth relaxes the bowels and mollifies acridities; %0aswallows’ dung, too, with honey, employed as a suppository, %0aacts as a purgative. %0a%0aCIIAF. 22.-REMEDIES FOR DISEASES OF THE FUNDAMENT AND OF %0a%0aTHE GENERATIVE ORGANS. %0a%0aThe most efficacious remedies for diseases of the rectum are %0awool-grease—to which some add pompholix 8 and oil of roses— %0aa dog’s head reduced to ashes; or a serpent’s slough, with %0avinegar. In cases where there are chaps and fissures ot those %0aparts, the ashes of the white portion of dogs’ dung are used, %0amixed with oil of roses ; a prescription due, they say, to iEscu- %0alapius, 9 and remarkably efficacious also for the removal of %0awarts. Ashes of burnt mouse-dung, swan’s fat, and cow %0asuet, are also used. Procidence of the rectum is reduced by an %0aapplication of the juices discharged by snails when punctured. %0aFor the cure of excoriation of those parts, ashes of burnt wood- %0amice are used, with honey; the gall of a hedge-bog, with a %0abat’s brains and bitches’ milk ; goose-grease, with the brains of %0athe bird, alum, and wool-grease; or else pigeons’ dung, mixed %0awith honey. A spider, the head and legs being first removed, %0ais remarkably good as a friction for condylomata. To prevent %0athe acridity of the humours from fretting the flesh, goose- %0agrease is applied, with Punic wax, white lead, and oil of %0aroses; swan’s grease also, which is said to be a cure for piles. %0a%0aA very good thing, they say, lor sciatica, is, to pound raw %0asnails in Aminean 10 wine, and to take them with pepper; to %0aeat a green lizard, the feet, head, and intestines being fiist %0aremoved; or to eat a spotted lizard, with the addition ot three %0aoboli of black poppy. Ruptures and convulsions are treated %0awith sheep’s gall, diluted with woman’s milk. The gravy which %0aescapes from a ram’s lights roasted, is used for the cure ot %0aitching pimples and warts upon the generative ^oigans. tor %0aother affections of those parts, the ashes of a ram s wool, un¬ %0awashed even, are used, applied with water; the suet ot a %0asheep’s caul, and of the kidneys more particularly, mixed with %0aashes of pumice-stone and salt; greasy wool, app led. with cold %0awater; sheep’s flesh, burnt to ashes, and applied with water; %0a%0a8 See B. xxxiv. c. 33. 9 It can hardly be said to add to his fame. %0a%0a10 Sec B. xiv. c. 4. %0a%0a%0a446 %0a%0a%0apliny’s natural distort. %0a%0a%0a[Rook XXX. %0a%0a%0aa mule’s hoofs, burnt to ashes; or the powder of pounded %0ahorse teeth, sprinkled upon the parts. In cases ot decidence %0aof either of the testes, an application of the slime discharged %0aby snails is remedial, they say. For the treatment of sordid %0aor running ulcers of those parts, the fresh ashes of a burnt %0adog’s head are found highly useful; the small, broad kind of %0asnail, beaten up in vinegar ; a snake’s slough, or the ashes of %0ait, applied in vinegar; honey in which the bees have died, %0amixed with resin; or the kind of snail without a shell, that is %0afound in Africa, as already 11 mentioned, beaten up with pow¬ %0adered frankincense and white of eggs, the application being %0arenewed at the end of thirty days; some persons, however, %0asubstitute a bulb for the frankincense. %0a%0aFor the cure of hydrocele, a spotted lizard, they say, is %0amarvellously good, the head, feet, and intestines being first %0aremoved, and the rest of the body roasted and taken frequently %0awith the food. For incontinence' 2 of urine dogs’ fat is used, %0amixed with a piece of split alum the size of a bean; ashes, %0aalso, of African snails burnt with the shells, taken in drink ; %0aor else the tongues of three geese roasted and eaten with the %0afood, a remedy which we owe to Anaxilaiis. Mutton-suet, 13 %0amixed with parched salt, has an aperient effect upon inflam¬ %0amatory tumours, and mouse-dung, mixed with powdered %0afrankincense and sandarach, acts upon them as a dispellent: %0athe ashes, also, of a burnt lizard, or the lizard itself, split %0aasunder and applied; or else bruised millepedes, mixed with one %0athird part of turpentine. Some make use of earth of Sinope 14 %0afor this purpose, mixed with a bruised snail. Ashes of %0aempty snail-shells burnt alone, mixed with wax, possess cer¬ %0atain repercussive properties ; the same, too, with pigeons’ dung, %0aemployed by itself, or applied with oat-meal or barley-meal. %0aCantharides, mixed with lime, remove inflammatory tumours %0aquite as effectually as the lancet; and small snails, applied %0atopically with honey, have a soothing effect upon tumours in %0athe groin. %0a%0a11 In B. xxix. c. 36 and in c. 10 of this Book. %0a%0a12 See B. xxxii. c. 35. %0a%0a13 Ajasson remarks that this may probably be useful. %0a%0a11 See B. xxxv. cc. 12, 13. %0a%0a%0aChap. 23.] REMEDIES FOR DISEASES OF THE FEET. %0a%0a%0a447 %0a%0a%0aCHAT. 23. (9.)-REMEDIES FOR GOUT AND FOR DISEASES OF THE %0a%0aFEET. %0a%0aTo prevent varicose veins, the legs of children are rubbed %0awith a lizard’s blood : but both the party who operates and the %0apatient must be fasting at the time. Wool-grease, mixed with %0awoman’s milk and white lead, has a soothing effect upon gout; %0athe liquid dung also voided by sheep; a sheep’s lights; a %0arain’s gal