th %0athe food. Matter vomited by a dog, we are assured, applied %0ato the abdomen, will draw off the water that has accumulated %0athere. %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 32. (12).-REMEDIES FOR ERYSIPELAS. %0a%0aFor the cure of erysipelas, wool-grease is used, with pora- %0apholix 41 and oil of roses; the blood 42 also extracted from a tick; %0aearth worms, applied in vinegar ; or else a cricket crushed be¬ %0atween the hands—the good effect of this last being that the per¬ %0ason who uses this precaution before the malady has made its %0aappearance, will be preserved therefrom for a whole year. Care %0amust be taken also that iron is used for the removal of the %0acricket, with some of the earth about its hole. Goose-grease %0ais also employed for this purpose ; a viper’s head, dried and %0aburnt, and applied with vinegar ; or a serpent’s slough, applied %0ato the body, immediately after the bath, with bitumen and %0alamb suet. %0a%0a40 The “wolf” spider. See c. 17 of this Book. %0a%0a41 See B. xxxiv. c. 33. %0a%0a42 Ajasson remarks that, in reality, this is not blood, but a kind of %0aviscous liquid. %0a%0a%0aChap. 36.] REMEDIES FOR AFFECTIONS OF THE SINEWS. 457 • %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 33.-REMEDIES FOR CARBUNCLES. %0a%0aCarbuncles are removed by an application of pigeons’ dung, %0acither alone or in combination with linseed and oxymel; or %0aof bees that have died in the honey. A sprinkling of polenta %0aupon the sores is also used. For carbuncles and other sores of %0athe generative organs, wool-grease is used as a remedy, with %0arefuse of lead; and for incipient carbuncles, sheep’s dung is %0aemployed. Tumours and all other affections that stand in need %0aof emollients are treated most effectually with goose-grease; %0athat of cranes, too, is equally efficacious. %0a%0aCHAP. 34.-REMEDIES FOR BOILS. %0a%0aFor boils the following remedies are prescribed'; a spider, %0aapplied before mentioning the insect by name, care being %0ataken to remove it at the end of two days; a shrew-mouse, %