pasms: and the dried %0aliver of a kite, taken in doses of three oboli, in three cyathi %0aof hydromel, is a preservative agaiust opisthotony. %0a%0aCHAP. 37. -REMEDIES FOR MALADIES OF THE NAILS AND FINGERS. %0a%0aAgnails and hangnails upon the fingers are removed by %0ausing the ashes of a burnt dog’s head, or the uterus of a bitch %0aboiled in oil, the fingers being first rubbed with a liniment of %0aewe-milk butter, mixed with honey. The gall-bladder, too, of %0aany animal is very useful for this purpose. Malformed nails %0aare healed with an application of cantharides and pitch, which %0ais removed at the end of two days ; or else with locusts fried %0awith he-goat suet; or with an application of mutton suet. Some %0amix mistletoe and purslain with these ingredients; while %0aothers, again, use verdigrease and mistletoe, removing the appli¬ %0acation at the end of two days. %0a%0aCHAP. 38. (13.) —METHODS FOR ARRESTING HAEMORRHAGE. %0a%0aBleeding at the nostrils is arrested by mutton suet taken %0afrom the caul, introduced into the nostrils; by drawing up %0arennet, lamb’s rennet in particular, mixed with water, into the %0anostrils, or by using it as an injection, a remedy which succeeds %0aeven where other remedies have failed; by making up goose- %0agrease into a bolus with an equal quantity of butter, and %0aplugging the nostrils with it; or by using the earth that %0aadheres to snails, or else the snails themselves, extracted from %0athe shell. Excessive discharges from the nostrils are arrested %0aalso by applying crushed snails, or cobwebs, to the forehead. %0aFor issues of blood from the brain, the blood or brains of %0apoultry are used, as also pigeons’ dung, thickened and kept %0afor the purpose. In cases where there is an immoderate flow %0aof blood from a wound, an application of horse-dung, burnt %0awith egg-shells, is marvellously good for stopping it. %0a%0aCHAP. 39. —REMEDIES FOR ULCEROUS SORES AND WOUNDS. %0a%0aFor the cure of ulcers, wool-grease is used, with ashes of %0a%0a%0aChap. "9.j %0a%0a%0aREMEDIES FOR WOUNDS. %0a%0a%0a459 %0a%0a%0aburnt barley and verdigrease, in equal quantities; a prepa¬ %0aration which is good, too, for carcinomata and spreading sores. %0aIt cauterizes the flesh also around the margins of ulcers, and %0areduces and makes level fungous excrescences formed by sores. %0aAshes, too, of burnt sheep’s dung, mixed with nitre, are of great %0aefficacy for the cure of carcinomata; as also those of lambs’ %0athigh-bones, in cases more particularly where ulcers refuse to %0acicatrize. Very considerable, too, is the efficacy of lights, %0aram’s lights in particular, which are of the greatest utility tor %0areducing and making level the fleshy excrescences formed by %0aulcerous sores. With sheep’s dung, warmed beneath an %0aearthen pan and kneaded, the swellings attendant upon wounds %0aare reduced, and fistulous sores and epinyctis are cleansed and %0amade to heal. %0a%0aBut it is in the ashes of a burnt dog s head that the %0agreatest efficacy is found; as it quite equals spodiunfl 3 in %0aits property of cauterizing all kinds of fleshy excrescences, %0aand causing sores to heal. Mouse-dung, too, is used as a %0acautery, and weasels’ dung, burnt to ashes. Pounded mille¬ %0apedes, mixed with turpentine and earth of Sinope ,' 16 are used %0afor penetrating carcinomata and fleshy indurations in deep- %0aseated sores ; and the same substances are remarkably useful %0afor the treatment of ulcers threatened with maggots. %0a%0aIndeed the several varieties of worms themselves are pos¬ %0asessed of marvellously useful properties. Ihe worms, lor %0ainstance, that breed in wood are curative of all kinds of ulcers : %0areduced to ashes, with an equal quantity of anise, and applied %0awith oil, they heal cancerous sores. Earthworms are so remark¬ %0aably healing for wounds recently inflicted, that it is a very %0ageneral belief that by the end of seven days they will unite %0asinews even that have been cut asunder : hence it is that it is re¬ %0acommended to keep them preserved in honey. Ashes of burnt %0aearth-worms, in combination with tar or Simblian honey, cau¬ %0aterize the indurated margins of ulcerous sores. Some persons dry %0aearthworms in the sun, and apply them to wounds with vinegar, %0athe application not beingremoved till the end of acouple of daj s. %0aThe earth also that adheres to snails is useful, similarly ern- %0a%0a%0a45 See B. xxxiv. c. 34. %0a%0a46 See B. xxxv. cc. 12, 13. %0a%0a47 Dioscorides speaks of this honey %0a%0a%0a*7 “ Cosses.” %0aas the produce of Sicily. %0a%0a%0a4 GO %0a%0a%0apunt’s natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Rook XXX. %0a%0a%0aployed; snails, too, taken whole from the shell, are pounded %0aand applied to fresh wounds, to heal them, and they arrest the %0aprogress of cancerous sores. %0a%0aThere is an insect called “herpes” 49 h)' the Greeks, which %0ais particularly useful for the cure of all kinds of serpiginous 40 %0asores. Snails, beaten up, shells and all, are very good tor this %0apurpose ; and it is said that, with myrrh and frankincense, %0athey will unite the sinews even when cut asunder. The fat, %0atoo, of a dragon, 61 dried in the sun, is remarkably useful, and %0aso are the brains of a cock or capon for recent wounds. By %0ataking with the food salt in Avhich vipers have been preserved, %0aulcers are rendered more easy of treatment, it is said, and are %0amade to heal all the sooner. Antonius 52 the physician, after %0aoperating in vain upon ulcers, that were incurable with the %0aknife, used to prescribe viper’s flesh to be eaten by the patient, %0awhereby a marvellously speedy cure was effected. %0a%0aThe locust called “ troxallis,” 53 reduced to ashes and applied %0awith honey, removes the indurated margins of ulcerous sores: %0aashes, also, of burnt pigeons’ dung, with arsenic and honey, %0aare very effectual in all cases -where a cautery is required. %0aThe brains of a horned owl, applied with goose-grease, ar