t before the end of two days: cantha- %0alides, also, bruised and applied with barley-meal, are highly %0aextolled. %0a%0aCUAP. 43. (14.)- REMEDIES FOR FEMALE COMPLAINTS. %0a%0aFor diseases incident to females, a ewe s placenta is very %0auseful, as already 66 mentioned by us, when speaking ot goats: %0asheep’s dung, too, is equally good. A fumigation of burnt %0alocusts, applied to the lower parts, affords relief to strangury, %0ain females more particularly. If, immediately after concep¬ %0ation, a woman eats a cock’s testes every now and then, the %0achild of which she is pregnant will become 67 a male, it is said. %0aThe ashes of a burnt porcupine, taken in drink, are a preventive %0aof abortion : bitches’ milk facilitates delivery: and the after¬ %0abirth of a bitch, provided it has not touched the ground, will %0aact as an expellent of the foetus. Milk, taken as a drink, %0astrengthens the loins of women when in travail. Mouse-dung, %0adiluted with rain water, reduces the breasts of females, when %0aswollen after delivery. The ashes of a burnt hedge-hog, %0aapplied with oil, act as a preventive of abortion. Delivery is %0afacilitated, in cases where the patient has taken, either goose- %0adung in two cyathi of water, or the liquid that escapes from %0athe uterus of a weasel by its genitals. %0a%0aEarth-worms, applied topically, effectually prevent pains in %0athe sinews of the neck and shoulders; taken in raisin wine, %0athey expel the after-birth, when retarded. Applied by them¬ %0aselves, earthworms ripen abscesses of the breasts, open them, %0adraw the humours, and make them cicatrize : taken in honied %0awine, they promote the secretion of the milk. In hay-grass there %0aare small worms found, which, attached to the neck, act as a %0apreventive of premature delivery; they are removed, however, %0aat the moment of childbirth, as otherwise they would have the %0aeffect of impeding delivery; care must be taken, also, not to put %0a56 In B. xxviii. c. 77. 67 “