is cured by letting a green %0alizard bite the child’s body while asleep, after which the lizard %0ais attached to a reed, and hung up in the smoke; by the time %0athe animal dies, the child will bo perfectly cured, it is said. %0aThe slime of snails, applied to the eyes of children, straightens %0athe eyelashes, and makes them grow. Ashes of burnt snails, %0aapplied with frankincense and juice of white grapes, are a cure %0afor hernia [in infants], if applied for thirty days consecutively. %0aWithin the horns 71 of snails, there are certain hard substances %0afound, like grits of sand : attached to infants, they facilitate %0adentition. %0a%0aAshes of empty snail-shells, mixed with wax, are a pre¬ %0aventive of procidence of the rectum ; but they must be used %0ai'l combination with the matter that exudes from a viper’s %0abrains, on the head being pricked. Vipers’ brains, attached to %0athe infant’s body in a piece of skin, facilitate dentition, a simi¬ %0alar effect being produced by using the larger teeth of. serpents. %0aHavens’ dung, attached to an infant with wool, is curative of %0acough. %0a%0aIt is hardly possible to preserve one’s seriousness in describing %0asome of these remedies, but as they have been transmitted to %0aus, I must not pass them in silence. For the treatment of %0ahernia in infants, a lizard is recommended ; but it must be a %0amale lizard, a thing that may be ascertained by its having but %0aone orifice beneath the tail. The method of proceeding, is for %0athe lizard to bite the part affected through cloth of gold, cloth %0aof silver, and cloth dyed purple; after which it is tied fast in a %0acup that has never been used, and smoked. Incontinence of %0aurine in infants is checked by giving them boiled mice 74 with %0atheir food. The large indented horns of the scarabaeus, attached %0ato the bodies of infants, have all the virtues of an amulet. In %0athe head of the boa 76 there is a small stone, they say, which %0athe serpent spits out,