ached to the body in the skin of a crane, %0aacts powerfully as a stimulant upon males : an effect equally %0aproduced by taking the yolks of five pigeons’ eggs, in honey, %0amixed with one denarius of hog’s lard; sparrows, or eggs of %0asparrows, with the food ; or by wearing the right testicle of a %0acock, attached to the body in a ram’s skin. The ashes of a %0aburnt ibis, it is said, employed as a friction with goose-grease %0aand oil of iris, will prevent abortion when a female has once %0aconceived ; while the testes of a game-cock, on the other hand, %0arubbed with goose-grease and attached to the body in a ram s %0askin, have all the effect of an antaphrodisiac: the same, too, %0awith the testes of any kind of dunghill cock, placed, together %0awith the blood of a cock, beneath the bed. Hairs taken from %0a%0aH H 2 %0a%0a%0a458 %0a%0a%0aPLINY’S NATURAL niSTORT. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXX. %0a%0a%0athe tail of a she-mule while being covered by the stallion, will %0amake a woman conceive, against her will even, if knotted %0atogether at the moment of the sexual congress. 17 If a man %0amakes water upon a dog's urine, he will become disinclined to %0acopulation, they say. %0a%0aA singular thing, too, is what is told about the ashes of a %0aspotted lizard—if indeed it is true—to the effect that, wrapped %0ain linen and held in the left hand, they act as an aphrodisiac, %0awhile, on the contrary, if they are transferred to the right, they %0awill take effect as an antaphrodisiac. A bat’s blood, too, they %0asay, received on a flock of wool and placed beneath a woman’s %0ahead, will promote sexual desire; the same being the case also %0awith a goose’s tongue, taken with the food or drink. %0a%0aCHAP. 50.-REMEDIES FOR PHTHIR1ASIS, AND FOR VARIOUS OTHEE %0a%0aAFFECTIONS. %0a%0aIn phthiriasis, all the vermin upon the body may be killed in %0athe course of three days, by taking the cast-off slough of a ser¬ %0apent, in drink, or else whey of milk after the cheese is removed, 