nimal it is, %0aor where it is to be found. That it did formerly exist, however, %0aI have no doubt, as certain remedies are described as being %0aderived from it. M. Cicero speaks of animals called “biuri,” 84 %0awhich gnaw the vines in Campania. %0a%0aCHAP. 53. (16.)-OTHER MARVELLOUS FACTS CONNECTED WITH %0a%0aANIMALS. %0a%0aThere are still some other marvellous facts related, with %0areference to the animals which we have mentioned. A dog %0awill not bark at a person who has any part of the secundines %0aof a bitch about him, or a hare’s dung or fur. The kind of %0agnats called “ muliones,” 85 do not live more than a single day. %0aPersons when taking honey from the hives, will never be %0atouched by the bees if they carry the beak of a wood-pecker 86 %0aabout them. Swine will be sure to follow the person who has %0agiven them a raven’s brains, made up into a bolus. The dust %0ain which a she-mule has wallowed, sprinkled upon the body, %0awill allay the flames of desire. Eats may be put to flight by %0acastrating a male rat, and setting it at liberty. If a snake s %0aslough is beaten up with some spelt, salt, and wild thyme, and %0aintroduced into the throat of oxen, with wine, at the time %0athat grapes are ripening, they will be in perfect health for a %0awhole year to come : the same, too, if three young swallows are %0agiven to them, made up into three boluses. The dust gathered %0afrom the track of a snake, sprinkled among bees, will make %0a%0a%0a81 Possibly a kind of crane. %0a%0a82 See B. viii. c. 75, and B. xxviii. c. 42. %0a%0a83 It has not been identified. . %0a%0a84 Hardouin thinks that the worm called by the Greeks is meant. %0a%0aOvid speaks in his Fasti, B. i. 11. 354-360, of the goat, as being very fond %0aof gnawing the vine. 85 See B. xi. c. 19. 86 See B. x. c. 20. %0a%0a%0a470 %0a%0a%0aFLINT’S NATURAL niSTORY. %0a%0a%0a[Oook XXX. %0a%0a%0athem return to the hive. If the right testicle of a ram 87 is %0atied up, he will generate females only. Persons who hare %0aabout them the sinews taken from the wings or legs of a crane, %0awill never be fatigued with any kind of laborious exertion. %0aMules will never kick when they have drunk wine. %0a%0aOf all known substances, it is a mule’6 88 hoofs only that are %0anot corroded by the poisonous waters of the fountain Styx : a %0amemorable discovery made by Aristotle, 89 to his great infamy, %0aon the occasion when Antipater sent some of this water to %0aAlexander the Great, for the purpose of poisoning him. %0a%0aWe will now pass on to the aquatic productions. %0a%0a%0aSummary. — Remedies, narratives, and observations, eight %0ahundred and fifty-four. %0a%0aRoman authors quoted. —M. Yarro, 90 Nigidius, 91 M. Cicero,” %0aSextius Niger 93 who wrote in Greek, Licinius Macer.* 4 %0a%0aForeign authors quoted. —Eudoxus, 95 Aristotle, 96 Hcrmip- %0apus, 97 Homer, Apion, 98 Orpheus, 99 Democritus, 1 Anaxilaus. 2 %0a%0aMedical authors quoted.— Botrys, 3 Horus, 4 Apollodorus, 0 %0aMenander, 6 Archidemus, 7 Aristogenes, 8 Xenocrates, 9 Diodorus, 10 %0aChrysippus, 11 Nicander, 12 Apollonius 13 of Pitanm. %0a%0a%0a87 See B. viii. c. 72. %0a%0a88 Some authorities say the ass, and others the Onager, or wild ass. %0a%0a89 This story is generally regarded as an absurdity, and is rejected by %0a%0aArrian and Plutarch. so g ee en ^ of B j; %0a%0a91 See end of B. vi. 99 See end of B. vii. 99 See end of B. xii. %0a%0a94 See end of B. xix. 95 See end of B. ii. 99 See end of B. ii. %0a%0a97 An eminent philosopher, a native of Smyrna, and disciple of Calli¬ %0amachus. lie flourished about the middle of'the third century n.c., and %0a%0aleft numerous works, the principal of which was a Biography of the Phi¬ %0alosophers, Poets, and Historians, which seems to have been highly esteemed. %0aIt is thought, too, that he wrote a work on Magic and Astrology: but there %0aare some doubts about the writer’s identity. %0a%0a98 A native of Oasis in Egypt, who taught rhetoric at Rome in the reigns %0