diff:1673559554:1673559554:=1,2838d0%0a%3c BOOK XXX. %0a%3c %0a%3c REMEDIES DERIVED FROM LIVING CREATURES. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 1. (1.)-THE ORIGIN OF THE MAGIC ART. %0a%3c %0a%3c In former parts of this work, I have had occasion more than %0a%3c once, when the subject demanded it, to refute the impostures %0a%3c of the magic art, and it is now my intention to continue still %0a%3c further my exposure thereof. Indeed, there are few subjects %0a%3c on which more might be profitably said, were it only that, %0a%3c being, as it is, the most deceptive of all known arts, it has %0a%3c exercised the greatest influence in every country and in nearly %0a%3c every age. And no one can be surprised at the extent of its %0a%3c influence and authority, when he reflects that by its own ener¬ %0a%3c gies it has embraced, and thoroughly amalgamated with itself, %0a%3c the three other sciences 1 which hold the greatest sway upon %0a%3c the mind of man. %0a%3c %0a%3c That it first originated in medicine, no one entertains a %0a%3c doubt ; 2 or that, under the plausible guise of promoting health, %0a%3c it insinuated itself among mankind, as a higher and more holy %0a%3c brauch of the medical art. Then, in the next place, to pro¬ %0a%3c mises the most seductive and the most flattering, it has added %0a%3c all the resources of religion, a subject upon which, at the pre¬ %0a%3c sent day, man is still entirely in the dark. Last of all, to %0a%3c complete its universal sway, it has incorporated with itself the %0a%3c astrological art ; 3 there being no man who is not desirous to %0a%3c know his future destiny, or who is not ready to believe that %0a%3c this knowledge may with the greatest certainty be obtained, %0a%3c by observing the face of the heavens. The senses of men %0a%3c being thus enthralled by a three-fold bond, the art of magic %0a%3c has attained an influence so mighty, that at the present day %0a%3c even, it holds sway throughout a great part of the world, and %0a%3c rules the