gic Art, as practised by the ancients. Coffee-grounds, glair of %0a%3c eggs, and rose-leaves, are still used in France for purposes ot divination %0a%3c by the superstitious. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 428 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pliny’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXX. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c superstition, however barbarous and ferocious the rites which %0a%3c it sanctions, that is not more tolerant than the imaginations %0a%3c which he conceived, and owing to which, by a series of blood¬ %0a%3c stained crimes, our abodes were peopled with ghosts. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 6.—THE SUBTERFUGES PRACTISED BY THE MAGICIANS. %0a%3c %0a%3c The magicians, too, have certain modes of evasion, as, for %0a%3c instance, that the gods will not obey, or even appear to, persons %0a%3c who have freckles upon the skin. Was this perchance the %0a%3c obstacle 42 in Nero’s way ? As for his limbs, there was 43 nothing %0a%3c deficient in them. And then, besides, he was at liberty to %0a%3c make choice of the days prescribed by the magic ritual: it %0a%3c was an easy thing for him to make choice of sheep whose %0a%3c colour was no other than perfectly black: and as to sacrificing %0a%3c human beings, there was nothing in the world that gave him %0a%3c greater pleasure. The Magian Tiridates 44 was at his court, %0a%3c having repaired thither, in token of our triumph over Armenia, %0a%3c accompanied by a train which cost dear to the provinces through %0a%3c which it passed. For the fact was, that he was unwilling to %0a%3c travel by water, it being a maxim with the adepts in this art %0a%3c that it is improper to spit into the sea or to profane that element %0a%3c by any other of the evacuations that are inseparable from the %0a%3c infirmities of human nature. He brought with him, too, %0a%3c several other Magi, and went so far as to initiate the emperor %0a%3c in the repasts 45 of the craft; and yet the prince, for all he had %0a%3c bestowed a kingdom upon the stranger, found himself unable