 14.-REMEDIES FOE PAINS IN THE VISCERA. %0a%3c %0a%3c "We give the one general name of “ prsecordia” to the %0a%3c human viscera; for pains in any part of which, a sucking %0a%3c whelp is applied, being pressed close to the part affected. 78 The %0a%3c malady, it is said, will in such case pass into the animal; a %0a%3c fact which may be satisfactorily ascertained ; for on disembowel¬ %0a%3c ling it, and sprinkling the entrails with wine, that part of the %0a%3c viscera will be found affected in which the patient himself %0a%3c was sensible of pain: to bury the animal in such a case is a %0a%3c point most religiously observed. The dogs, 19 too, which we %0a%3c call “ Melifaei,” applied to the stomach every now and then, %0a%3c allay pains in that region : the malady, it is supposed, passes %0a%3c into the animal’s body, as it gradually loses its health, and %0a%3c it mostly dies. %0a%3c %0a%3c (6.) Affections of the lungs are cured by using mice, those of %0a%3c Africa more particularly, the animal being skinned and boiled %0a%3c in salt and oil, and then taken with the food. The same pre¬ %0a%3c paration is used also, for the cure of purulent or bloody ex¬ %0a%3c pectorations. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 15.-REMEDIES FOR PAINS IN THE STOMACH. %0a%3c %0a%3c ODe of the very best remedies for affections of the stomach, %0a%3c is to use a snail diet. 80 They must first be left to simmer in %0a%3c water for some time, without touching the contents of the %0a%3c shell, after which, without any other addition, they must be %0a%3c grilled upon hot coals, and eaten with wine and garum ; 81 the %0a%3c snails of Africa being the best of all for the purpose. The %0a%3c efficacy of this remedy has been proved in numerous instances %0a%3c of late. Another point, too, to be observed, is to take an un¬ %0a%3c even number of them. Snails, however, have a juice, it should %0a%3c he remembered, which imparts to the breath an offensive smell. %0a%3c %0a%3c 77 See Horace, Epode xii. 1. 5. %0a%