her Chrysippus has left a statement to %0a%3c the effect, that the phryganion, 39 worn as an amulet, is a %0a%3c remedy for quartan fevers; but what kind of animal this is he %0a%3c has nowhere informed us, nor have I been able to meet with %0a%3c any one who knows. Still, however, I felt myself bound to %0a%3c notice a remedy that was mentioned by an author of such high %0a%3c repute, in case any other person should happen to be more %0a%3c successful in his researches. To eat the flesh of a crow, and %0a%3c %0a%3c 38 See B. xi. c. 38. . , , , %0a%3c %0a%3c 39 Some suppose that this was an insect that lived among dry wood, %0a%3c and derive the name from the Greek %3cppvyavbv. Queslon is of opiuion that %0a%3c it is the salamander. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 456 pliny’s natural HISTORY. [Book XXX. %0a%3c %0a%3c to use nitre in the form of a liniment, is considered highly %0a%3c efficacious for the treatment of chronic diseases. %0a%3c %0a%3c In cases of tertian fever—so true it is that suffering takes %0a%3c delight in prolonging hope by trying every remedy—it may be %0a%3c worth while to make trial whether the web of the spider called %0a%3c “ lycos” 10 is of any use, applied, with the insect itself, to the %0a%3c temples and forehead in a compress covered with resin and wax; %0a%3c or the insect itself, attached to the body in a reed, a form in %0a%3c which it is said to be highly beneficial for other fevers. Trial %0a%3c may be made also of a greeu lizard, enclosed alive in a vessel %0a%3c just large enough to receive it, and worn as an amulet; a %0a%3c method, it is said, by which recurrent fevers are often dis¬ %0a%3c pelled. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 31.-11EMEDIKS FOR DROrSY. %0a%3c %0a%3c For the cure of dropsy, wool-grease, a piece about the size %0a%3c of a hazel-nut, is given in wine, with the addition of a little %0a%3c myrrh : some add goose-grease, steeped in myrtle wine. The %0a%3c filth that adheres to the udders of sheep is productive of a %0a%3c similar effect, as also the dried flesh of a hedge-hog, taken with %0a%3c the food. Matter vomited by a dog, we are assured, applied %0a%3c to the abdomen, will draw off the water that has accumulated %0a%3c there. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 32. (12).-REMEDIES FOR ERYSIPELAS. %0a%3c %0a%3c For the cure of erysipelas, wool-grease is used, with pora- %0a%3c pholix 41 and oil of roses; the blood 42 also extracted from a tick; %0a%3c earth worms, applied in vinegar ; or else a cricket crushed be¬ %0a%3c tween the hands—the good effect of this last being that the per¬ %0a%3c son who uses this precaution before the malady has made its %0a%3c appearance, will be preserved therefrom for a whole year. Care %0a%3c must be taken also that iron is used for the removal of the %0a%3c cricket, with some of the earth about its hole. Goose-grease %0a%3c is also employed for this purpose ; a viper’s head, dried and %0a%3c burnt, and applied with vinegar ; or a serpent’s slough, applied %0a%3c to the body, immediately after the bath, with bitumen and %0a%3c lamb suet. %0a%3c %0a%3c 40 The “wolf” spider. See c. 17 of this Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c 41 See B. xxxiv. c. 33. %0a%3c %0a%3c 42 Ajasson remarks that, in reality, this is not blood, but a kind of %0a%3c viscous liquid. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 36.] REMEDIES FOR AFFECTIONS OF THE SINEWS. 457 • %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 33.-REMEDIES FOR CARBUNCLES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Carbuncles are removed by an application of pigeons’ dung, %0a%3c cither alone or in combination with linseed and oxymel; or %0a%3c of bees that have died in the honey. A sprinkling of polenta %0a%3c upon the sores is also used. For carbuncles and other sores of %0a%3c the generative organs, wool-grease is used as a remedy, with %0a%3c refuse of lead; and for incipient carbuncles, sheep’s dung is %0a%3c employed. Tumours and all other affections that stand in need %0a%3c of emollients are treated most effectually with goose-grease; %0a%3c that of cranes, too, is equally efficacious. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 34.-REMEDIES FOR BOILS. %0a%3c %0a%3c For boils the following remedies are prescribed'; a spider, %0a%3c applied before mentioning the insect by name, care being %0a%3c taken to remove it at the end of two days; a shrew-mouse, %0a%3c suspended by the neck till it is dead, care being taken not %0a%3c to let it touch the earth when dead, and to pass it three %0a%3c times around the boil, both operator and patient spitting on the %0a%3c floor each time; poultry-dung, that of a red colour in particular, %0a%3c applied fresh with vinegar; the crop of a stork, boiled in wine; %0a%3c flies, an uneven number of them, rubbed upon the patient with %0a%3c the ring 43 finger ; the filth from sheep’s ears; stale mutton %0a%3c suet, with ashes of women’s hair; ram suet also, with ashes of %0a%3c burnt pumice and an equal quantity of salt. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 35.-REMEDIES FOR BURNS. %0a%3c %0a%3c For burns, the ashes of a dog’s head are used; ashes of %0a%3c burnt dormice, with oil; sheep’s dung, with wax; ashes also %0a%3c of burnt snails, an application so effectual, as not to leave a %0a%3c 6careven. Yiper’s fat, too, is used, and ashes of burnt pigeons’ %0a%3c dung, applied with oil. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 36.-REMEDIES FOR AFFECTIONS OF THE SINEWS. %0a%3c %0a%3c For nodosities in the sinews, the ashes of a viper’s head are %0a%3c applied, with oil of Cyprus ; 44 or else earth-worms, with honey, %0a%3c l’ains in the sinews should be treated with an application of %0a%3c grease; the body of a dead amphisbsena, worn as an amulet; %0a%3c vulture’s grease, dried with the crop of the bird and beaten up %0a%3c with stale hog’s lard ; or else ashes of the head of a horned %0a%3c %0a%3c « “Digitus medicus “ The physician’s finger,” properly. Why %0a%3c the fourth finger, or that next to the little finger, was thus called, it seems %0a%3c impossible to say. 44 ^ ee x ’ 4 - c - %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c * 458 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pliny’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Hook XXX. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c owl, taken in honied wine with a lily root—that is, il‘ we believe %0a%3c what the magicians tell ns. For contractions of the sinews, the %0a%3c flesh of ring-doves is very good, dried and taken with the food: %0a%3c and for spasmodic affections, the ashes of a hedge-hog or weasel %0a%3c are used. A serpent’s slough, attached to the patient’s body in %0a%3c a piece of bull’s hide, is a preventive of spasms: and the dried %0a%3c liver of a kite, taken in doses of three oboli, in three cyathi %0a%3c of hydromel, is a preservative agaiust opisthotony. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 37. -REMEDIES FOR MALADIES OF THE NAILS AND FINGERS. %0a%3c %0a%3c Agnails and hangnails upon the fingers are removed by %0a%3c using the ashes of a burnt dog’s head, or the uterus of a bitch %0a%3c boiled in oil, the fingers being first rubbed with a liniment of %0a%3c ewe-milk butter, mixed with honey. The gall-bladder, too, of %0a%3c any animal is very useful for this purpose. Malformed nails %0a%3c are healed with an application of cantharides and pitch, which %0a%3c is removed at the end of two days ; or else with locusts fried %0a%3c with he-goat suet; or with an application of mutton suet. Some %0a%3c mix mistletoe and purslain with these ingredients; while %0a%3c others, again, use verdigrease and mistletoe, removing the appli¬ %0a%3c cation at the end of two days. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 38. (13.) —METHODS FOR ARRESTING HAEMORRHAGE. %0a%3c %0a%3c Bleeding at the nostrils is arrested by mutton suet taken %0a%3c from the caul, introduced into the nostrils; by drawing up %0a%3c rennet, lamb’s rennet in particular, mixed with water, into the %0a%3c nostrils, or by using it as an injection, a remedy which succeeds %0a%3c even where other remedies have failed; by making up goose- %0a%3c grease into a bolus with an equal quantity of butter, and %0a%3c plugging the nostrils with it; or by using the earth that %0a%3c adheres to snails, or else the snails themselves, extracted from %0a%3c the shell. Excessive discharges from the nostrils are arrested %0a%3c also by applying crushed snails, or cobwebs, to the forehead. %0a%3c For issues of blood from the brain, the blood or brains of %0a%3c poultry are used, as also pigeons’ dung, thickened and kept %0a%3c for the purpose. In cases where there is an immoderate flow %0a%3c of blood from a wound, an application of horse-dung, burnt %0a%3c with egg-shells, is marvellously good for stopping it. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 39. —REMEDIES FOR ULCEROUS SORES AND WOUNDS. %0a%3c %0a%3c For the cure of ulcers, wool-grease is used, with ashes of %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. "9.j %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c REMEDIES FOR WOUNDS. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 459 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c burnt barley and verdigrease, in equal quantities; a prepa¬ %0a%3c ration which is good, too, for carcinomata and spreading sores. %0a%3c It cauterizes the flesh also around the margins of ulcers, and %0a%3c reduces and makes level fungous excrescences formed by sores. %0a%3c Ashes, too, of burnt sheep’s dung, mixed with nitre, are of great %0a%3c efficacy for the cure of carcinomata; as also those of lambs’ %0a%3c thigh-bones, in cases more particularly where ulcers refuse to %0a%3c cicatrize. Very considerable, too, is the efficacy of lights, %0a%3c ram’s lights in particular, which are of the greatest utility tor %0a%3c reducing and making level the fleshy excrescences formed by %0a%3c ulcerous sores. With sheep’s dung, warmed beneath an %0a%3c earthen pan and kneaded, the swellings attendant upon wounds %0a%3c are reduced, and fistulous sores and epinyctis are cleansed and %0a%3c made to heal. %0a%3c %0a%3c But it is in the ashes of a burnt dog s head that the %0a%3c greatest efficacy is found; as it quite equals spodiunfl 3 in %0a%3c its property of cauterizing all kinds of fleshy excrescences, %0a%3c and causing sores to heal. Mouse-dung, too, is used as a %0a%3c cautery, and weasels’ dung, burnt to ashes. Pounded mille¬ %0a%3c pedes, mixed with turpentine and earth of Sinope ,' 16 are used %0a%3c for penetrating carcinomata and fleshy indurations in deep- %0a%3c seated sores ; and the same substances are remarkably useful %0a%3c for the treatment of ulcers threatened with maggots. %0a%3c %0a%3c Indeed the several varieties of worms themselves are pos¬ %0a%3c sessed of marvellously useful properties. Ihe worms, lor %0a%3c instance, that breed in wood are curative of all kinds of ulcers : %0a%3c reduced to ashes, with an equal quantity of anise, and applied %0a%3c with oil, they heal cancerous sores. Earthworms are so remark¬ %0a%3c ably healing for wounds recently inflicted, that it is a very %0a%3c general belief that by the end of seven days they will unite %0a%3c sinews even that have been cut asunder : hence it is that it is re¬ %0a%3c commended to keep them preserved in honey. Ashes of burnt %0a%3c earth-worms, in combination with tar or Simblian honey, cau¬ %0a%3c terize the indurated margins of ulcerous sores. Some persons dry %0a%3c earthworms in the sun, and apply them to wounds with vinegar, %0a%3c the application not beingremoved till the end of acouple of daj s. %0a%3c The earth also that adheres to snails is useful, similarly ern- %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 45 See B. xxxiv. c. 34. %0a%3c %0a%3c 46 See B. xxxv. cc. 12, 13. %0a%3c %0a%3c 47 Dioscorides speaks of this honey %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c *7 “ Cosses.” %0a%3c as the produce of Sicily. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 4 GO %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c punt’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Rook XXX. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ployed; snails, too, taken whole from the shell, are pounded %0a%3c and applied to fresh wounds, to heal them, and they arrest the %0a%3c progress of cancerous sores. %0a%3c %0a%3c There is an insect called “herpes” 49 h)' the Greeks, which %0a%3c is particularly useful for the cure of all kinds of serpiginous 40 %0a%3c sores. Snails, beaten up, shells and all, are very good tor this %0a%3c purpose ; and it is said that, with myrrh and frankincense, %0a%3c they will unite the sinews even when cut asunder. The fat, %0a%3c too, of a dragon, 61 dried in the sun, is remarkably useful, and %0a%3c so are the brains of a cock or capon for recent wounds. By %0a%3c taking with the food salt in Avhich vipers have been preserved, %0a%3c ulcers are rendered more easy of treatment, it is said, and are %0a%3c made to heal all the sooner. Antonius 52 the physician, after %0a%3c operating in vain upon ulcers, that were incurable with the %0a%3c knife, used to prescribe viper’s flesh to be eaten by the patient, %0a%3c whereby a marvellously speedy cure was effected. %0a%3c %0a%3c The locust called “ troxallis,” 53 reduced to ashes and applied %0a%3c with honey, removes the indurated margins of ulcerous sores: %0a%3c ashes, also, of burnt pigeons’ dung, with arsenic and honey, %0a%3c are very effectual in all cases -where a cautery is required. %0a%3c The brains of a horned owl, applied with goose-grease, are %0a%3c marvellously efficacious for uniting wounds, it is said. For %0a%3c the malignant ulcer known as “ cacoethes,” 64 the ashes of a %0a%3c ram’s thigh-bones are used, mixed with woman’s milk, the sores %0a%3c being washed with linen cloths well rinsed. For the same %0a%3c purpose, the bird known as the screech-owl 55 is boiled in oil, %0a%3c ewe-milk butter and honey being added to the preparation, %0a%3c when properly dissolved. An application of bees that have %0a%3c died in the honey, acts emolliently upon the indurated margins %0a%3c of ulcerous sores; and for the cure of elephantiasis, the blood %0a%3c and ashes of a weasel are employed. Wounds and weals pro¬ %0a%3c duced by blows are effaced by an application of sheep-skins %0a%3c fresh from the body. %0a%3c %0a%3c chap. 40. —remedies for broken bones. %0a%3c %0a%3c For fractures of the joints, ashes of sheep’s thigh-bones are %0a%3c %0a%3c 49 The “ creeper.” It has not been identified. %0a%3c %0a%3c 50 Which are also called “ herpetic ” or “ creeping." %0a%3c 