 and root of agrimony ; the white part also ot %0a%3c poultry dung, kept in a horn box with stale oil; a bat’s blood ; %0a%3c or else the gall of a hedge-hog applied with water. Itch-scab %0a%3c is cured by using the brains of a horned owl, incorporated with %0a%3c saltpetre; but dog’s blood is the best thing to keep it in %0a%3c check. The small, broad, snail that is found, crushed and ap¬ %0a%3c plied topically, is an effectual cure tor itching sensations. %0a%3c %0a%3c CRAP. 42. -METHODS OF EXTR4CTING FOREIGN SUBSTANCES FROM %0a%3c %0a%3c THE BODY. %0a%3c %0a%3c Arrows, pointed weapons, and other foreign substances that %0a%3c require to be extracted from the body, aie removed by the %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 462 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pliny's natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Cook XXX. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c application of a mouse split asunder, or of a lizard more par¬ %0a%3c ticularly, similarly divided, or else the head only ot the animal, %0a%3c pounded with salt. The snails, too, that arc found in clusters %0a%3c upon leaves, are pounded and applied with their shells on ; as %0a%3c also those that are used us food, the shells being first removed, %0a%3c applied with hare’s rennet in particular. lhe bones of a %0a%3c snake, applied with the rennet of any four-footed animal, will %0a%3c produce a similar effect before the end of two days: cantha- %0a%3c lides, also, bruised and applied with barley-meal, are highly %0a%3c extolled. %0a%3c %0a%3c CUAP. 43. (14.)- REMEDIES FOR FEMALE COMPLAINTS. %0a%3c %0a%3c For diseases incident to females, a ewe s placenta is very %0a%3c useful, as already 66 mentioned by us, when speaking ot goats: %0a%3c sheep’s dung, too, is equally good. A fumigation of burnt %0a%3c locusts, applied to the lower parts, affords relief to strangury, %0a%3c in females more particularly. If, immediately after concep¬ %0a%3c tion, a woman eats a cock’s testes every now and then, the %0a%3c child of which she is pregnant will become 67 a male, it i