nd held in the left hand, they act as an aphrodisiac, %0a%3c while, on the contrary, if they are transferred to the right, they %0a%3c will take effect as an antaphrodisiac. A bat’s blood, too, they %0a%3c say, received on a flock of wool and placed beneath a woman’s %0a%3c head, will promote sexual desire; the same being the case also %0a%3c with a goose’s tongue, taken with the food or drink. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 50.-REMEDIES FOR PHTHIR1ASIS, AND FOR VARIOUS OTHEE %0a%3c %0a%3c AFFECTIONS. %0a%3c %0a%3c In phthiriasis, all the vermin upon the body may be killed in %0a%3c the course of three days, by taking the cast-off slough of a ser¬ %0a%3c pent, in drink, or else whey of milk after the cheese is removed, %0a%3c with a little salt, Cheese, it is said, will never become rotten %0a%3c with age or be touched by mice, if a weasel’s brains have been %0a%3c mixed with the rennet. It is asserted, too, that if the ashes of %0a%3c a burnt weasel are mixed with the cramming for chickens or %0a%3c young pigeons, they will be safe from the attacks of weasels. %0a%3c Beasts of burden, when troubled with pains in staling, find %0a%3c immediate relief, if a bat is attached to tho body ; and they are %0a%3c effectually cured of bots by passing a ring-dove three times %0a%3c round their generative parts—a truly marvellous thing to relate, %0a%3c the ring-dove, on being set at liberty, dies, and the beast is in¬ %0a%3c stantly relieved from pain. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 51.-REMEDIES FOR INTOXICATION. %0a%3c %0a%3c The eggs of an owlet, administered to drunkards three days %0a%3c in wine, are productive of a distaste for that liquor. A sheep’s %0a%3c lights roasted, eaten before drinking, 78 act as a preventive of %0a%3c inebriety. The ashes of a swallow’s beak, bruised with myrrh %0a%3c and sprinkled in the wine, act as a preservative against intoxica¬ %0a%3c tion : Horus, 79 king of Assyria, was the first to discover thisA %0a%3c %0a%3c 77 “ Inter se conligat® in coitu.” %0a%3c %0a%3