g a male rat, and setting it at liberty. If a snake s %0a%3c slough is beaten up with some spelt, salt, and wild thyme, and %0a%3c introduced into the throat of oxen, with wine, at the time %0a%3c that grapes are ripening, they will be in perfect health for a %0a%3c whole year to come : the same, too, if three young swallows are %0a%3c given to them, made up into three boluses. The dust gathered %0a%3c from the track of a snake, sprinkled among bees, will make %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 81 Possibly a kind of crane. %0a%3c %0a%3c 82 See B. viii. c. 75, and B. xxviii. c. 42. %0a%3c %0a%3c 83 It has not been identified. . %0a%3c %0a%3c 84 Hardouin thinks that the worm called by the Greeks is meant. %0a%3c %0a%3c Ovid speaks in his Fasti, B. i. 11. 354-360, of the goat, as being very fond %0a%3c of gnawing the vine. 85 See B. xi. c. 19. 86 See B. x. c. 20. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 470 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c FLINT’S NATURAL niSTORY. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Oook XXX. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c them return to the hive. If the right testicle of a ram 87 is %0a%3c tied up, he will generate females only. Persons who hare %0a%3c about them the sinews taken from the wings or legs of a crane, %0a%3c will never be fatigued with any kind of laborious exertion. %0a%3c Mules will never kick when they have drunk wine. %0a%3c %0a%3c Of all known substances, it is a mule’6 88 hoofs only that are %0a%3c not corroded by the poisonous waters of the fountain Styx : a %0a%3c memorable discovery made by Aristotle, 89 to his great infamy, %0a%3c on the occasion when Antipater sent some of this water to %0a%3c Alexander the Great, for the purpose of poisoning him. %0a%3c %0a%3c We will now pass on to the aquatic productions. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Summary. — Remedies, narratives, and observations, eight %0a%3c hundred and fifty-four. %0a%3c %0a%3c Roman authors quoted. —M. Yarro, 90 Nigidius, 91 M. Cicero,” %0a%3c Sextius Niger 93 who wrote in Greek, Licinius Macer.* 4 %0a%3c %0a%3c Foreign authors quoted. —Eudoxus